<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<appendix xml:id="appG-computational-labs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Computational Labs Quick Reference</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Computers are useful in multivariable calculus for three jobs:
    </p>
    <table xml:id="tab-appG-three-jobs">
      <title>Three jobs a computer does in multivariable calculus.</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell>Job</cell>
          <cell>Use</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>visualize</cell>
          <cell>surfaces, contours, vector fields, flows</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>approximate</cell>
          <cell>derivatives, integrals, differential equations</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>check algebra</cell>
          <cell>symbolic derivatives, Jacobians, line and surface integrals</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      This appendix gives compact lab recipes. It uses Python-style notation, with
      <c>NumPy</c>, <c>Matplotlib</c>, <c>SciPy</c>, and <c>SymPy</c>. The mathematics
      does not depend on the software.
    </p>
    <table xml:id="tab-appG-task-to-tool">
      <title>Each mathematical task and the computational tool that fits it.</title>
      <tabular>
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell>Mathematical task</cell>
          <cell>Computational tool</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>z=f(x,y)</m></cell>
          <cell>surface plot</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>f(x,y)=c</m></cell>
          <cell>contour plot</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\mathbf F(x,y)</m></cell>
          <cell>quiver or stream plot</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>DF(\mathbf p)</m></cell>
          <cell>finite differences or symbolic Jacobian</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\iint_R f\,dA</m></cell>
          <cell>iterated integral, midpoint rule, Monte Carlo</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\int_C \omega</m></cell>
          <cell>parametrize and substitute</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\iint_S \Phi</m></cell>
          <cell>parametrize and use <m>\mathbf r_u\times\mathbf r_v</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\mathbf r'=\mathbf F(\mathbf r)</m></cell>
          <cell>ODE solver</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </introduction>

